sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K824008
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: We digested the promoter responsive to Cadmium (BBa_K174015) with EcoRI and SpeI and digested the GFP plasmid (BBa_I13401) with XbaI and PstI. The promoter was Chloramphenicol resistant and the GFP was Ampicillin resistant. These digested fragments were mixed and ligated to the provided, linearized pSB3C1 plasmid. The ligation mix was grown under Chloramphenicol selection. The resulting colonies were tested for responsive GFP production from the addition of Cadmium and Arsenic, respectively.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Steven Allen
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: This part is a combination of 2007 Brown's iGEM part BBa_K174015 and MIT's part (from 2005) I13401.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K174015
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
This Cadmium sensor has binding sites for ArsR and CzrA metal sensors. By placing them together, our device works as an AND gate and senses Cadmium when both proteins bind to Cadmium.
When Cadmium is not present both proteins bind to their relevant sites on the promoter and represses the expression of downstream genes. When Cadmium present in the environment, it binds to these repressors which then fall of from where they are bound to on the promoter. Hence the promoter becomes free to express the downstream genes as an indication of Cadmium.
This combinatorial approach enables us to filter out sensing other metals. ArsR and CzrA can bind to different metals, however when both are used as an ANd gate, they will only recognize Cadmium.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: The Newcastle 2009 iGEM team
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: CadA promoter which has the binding site for CzrA protein is combined with ArsR binding site to create this AND gate Cadmium sensor.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: We wanted to sense Cadmium accurately and used a combinatorial approach to achieve our goal.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_I13401
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: GFP reporter for RHS of library test constructs
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This part will be suffixed to a promoter.RBS library. The purpose of the experiment is to make a first pass at a library-based construction step to identify efficiency issues and also to examine maxPOPS/RIPS level.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: jasonk
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: This part was built by Jen as an intermediate to their nuts and bolts parts.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K174016
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This part purely holds the binding site for ArsR protein which can be released when bound to different metals. Hence this part can be combined with any promoter to sense metals that can bind to ArsR protein. When added in front of a promoter with another metal sensor's protein's binding site, it can form an AND gate to sensitively detect specific metals.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: The Newcastle 2009 iGEM team
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: It was developed mainly to use combinatorial approaches for metal sensing.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K174017
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: CadA promoter with CzrA binding site
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
In ''B. subtilis'' CadA system works as an efflux system to take the metals out in the cell. It is normally repressed by CzrA repressor protein. When certain metals get inside the cell, they can bind to CzrA and derepress the promoter expressing CadA. Hence metals are taken out by the efflux system.
By taking the promoter of CadA system, we created a generic metal sensor. Hence when it is combined with coding sequences of other genes, it will regulate the expression of these genes upon sensing metals.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: The Newcastle 2009 iGEM team
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: It is taken from ''B. subtilis'' ''cadA'' promoter.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: It was developed mainly to use combinatorial approaches for metal sensing

sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Transcriptional terminator consisting of a 64 bp stem-loop.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Randy Rettberg

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0012
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Transcription terminator for the E.coli RNA polymerase.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Derived from the TE terminator of T7 bacteriophage between Genes 1.3 and 1.4 <genbank>V01146</genbank>.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Suggested by Sri Kosuri and Drew Endy as a high efficiency terminator. The 5' end cutoff was placed immediately after the TAA stop codon and the 3' end cutoff was placed just prior to the RBS of Gene 1.4 (before AAGGAG).

Use anywhere transcription should be stopped when the gene of interest is upstream of this terminator.
